<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Koeberlinia spinosa </i>(a CNPS list 2.2 plant) is an intricately branched, leafless shrub to 4 m in height with rigid, dark-green stems that end in stout thorns. Fruits are black berries. This plant is easily confused with <i>Ziziphus obtusifolia </i>with gray branches, and with <i>Castela emoryi </i>with persistent, black capsules. California plants represent ssp. <i>tenuispina</i>; they are known from five locations in the Sonoran Desert. The species also grows in Bolivia. The typical form is a Chihuahuan Desert plant (Turner et al. 1995). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
